         <abstract>
            <p>The courts' interpretation of the prudent man rule employed by most states prior to the passage of ERISA conflicted with three important principles of modern investing: (1) It focused on the performance of individual securities, rather than on the performance of the portfolio as a whole; (2) it gave short shrift to diversification as an investment objective; and (3) it emphasized avoidance of capital loss at any cost, rather than evaluation of returns relative to risks incurred. By replacing the prudent man in his personal affairs with the prudent expert, ERISA has opened up pension fund management to modern investment practice.</p>
          </abstract>
